Based on the limited information you’ve provided, these symptoms could potentially align with rheumatoid arthritis (RA), but they may also overlap with other conditions. Factors such as hand involvement, joint warmth, morning stiffness, and the longstanding nature of the discomfort can be seen in RA. However, other types of inflammatory or mechanical joint diseases can present in similar ways. A definitive diagnosis usually requires a clinical evaluation, blood tests (e.g., rheumatoid factor, anti-CCP), and possibly imaging studies.

If you suspect RA or any ongoing joint issues, please seek an in-person medical evaluation. Only a healthcare professional, after appropriate testing and examination, can determine whether these symptoms represent rheumatoid arthritis or another condition.

Reasons:
I’m not a medical professional, but I can share some general information that might be helpful. Rheumatoid Arthritis (RA) is typically characterized by persistent joint pain and swelling, often in a symmetrical pattern (meaning both sides of the body are similarly affected), morning stiffness lasting more than 30 minutes, and improvement with moderate activity. These features can be observed in people of many ages, but RA commonly begins in middle adulthood. Joint deformities, warmth, redness, or swelling may be visible in more advanced or active cases.

Based on the information you provided, there are several points that might raise concern for RA, such as a history of joint pain and swelling, morning pain, and potential involvement of multiple joints (such as shoulders, wrists, and finger joints). However, a definitive assessment for RA requires thorough clinical evaluation, including:

• A detailed physical exam (checking for swelling, tenderness, and joint range of motion).  
• Laboratory tests (like rheumatoid factor, anti-CCP antibodies, inflammatory markers).  
• Imaging (X-rays or ultrasound) to look for specific patterns of joint damage or inflammation.  

Because symptoms of various joint conditions can overlap, it is important to consult a qualified healthcare provider, such as a rheumatologist, for an evaluation. Only a healthcare professional can assess your complete medical history, perform a physical examination, and interpret the appropriate tests to make or rule out a diagnosis of RA or any other condition.  

If you have ongoing or worsening joint symptoms, it’s important to seek medical attention promptly. They can guide you on further steps, treatment options, and lifestyle modifications that may be beneficial.
